	<!--Pedia Concepts-->
	<Language_en_US>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CITIES_HEALTH_HEADING3_TITLE">
			<Text>[COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]City Health[ENDCOLOR]</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CITIES_HEALTH_HEADING3_BODY">
			<Text>
				A City's [ICON_HEALTH] Health is based on its access to fresh water, resources, features, population, and buildings. City health is magnified by the Empire's Health Multiplier (see [COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]Empire Health[ENDCOLOR]).
				[NEWLINE]
				[NEWLINE]A City's overall health changes its [ICON_FOOD] Food stores each turn: positive values increase stores, while negative values reduce them. Health cannot force a city to grow, nor reduce its population.
				[NEWLINE]Unhealthy cities are much more likely to spawn, propagate and suffer from [ICON_PLAGUE] Plagues.
			</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_EMPIRE_HEALTH_HEADING3_TITLE">
			<Text>[COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]Empire Health[ENDCOLOR]</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_EMPIRE_HEALTH_HEADING3_BODY">
			<Text>
				The Empire's [ICON_HEALTH] Health is based on acquired Technologies, Policies and current [ICON_HAPPINESS_1] Happiness.
				[NEWLINE]Empire Health modifies every City's health by the current percent each turn (see [COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]City Health[ENDCOLOR]).
				[NEWLINE]
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Resource Diversity
				[NEWLINE]Each type of health resource available in the Empire (includes trades), adds 1% to Empire Health. Multiple copies of the same health resource do not stack.
			</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CITIES_PLAGUE_HEADING3_TITLE">
			<Text>[COLOR_NEGATIVE_TEXT]Plague[ENDCOLOR]</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CITIES_PLAGUE_HEADING3_BODY">
			<Text>
				[ICON_PLAGUE] Plagues can only begin in cities with negative [ICON_HEALTH] Health. Plagues may spread to nearby cities, cross international borders, and propagate to distant cities over land and sea routes.
				[NEWLINE]
				[NEWLINE][COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]Plague Effects[ENDCOLOR]
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]City Health is reduced by an amount equal to the current turns of Plague.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Negative Health will cause population loss if city [ICON_FOOD] Food stores are depleted during a Plague.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Positive Health is not added to [ICON_FOOD] Food stores during a Plague.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET][ICON_CAPITAL] Capitals will never decrease below 3[ICON_CITIZEN] Citizens.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Building an Academy with a Great Scientist instantly cures that player's plagued cities.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Plagued cities cannot heal, and can spread the plague to nearby cities.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Units in and near plagued cities will take damage each turn.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Units can catch the [COLOR_NEGATIVE_TEXT]Plagued Promotion[ENDCOLOR] when near plagued cities, which reduces their defensive abilities and lowers the health of adjacent cities.
				[NEWLINE]
				[NEWLINE][COLOR_POSITIVE_TEXT]Plague Propagation[ENDCOLOR]
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]World size, game speed, difficulty, and current era all effect how fast and how far plagues will spread.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]In general, plagues spread fastest in the Medieval Era and slower in later eras.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]In general, plagues spread further in later eras, but are mostly local in the Ancient and Classical Eras.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Open Borders and International Trade Routes will speed the spread of plagues into foreign lands.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Civs that are Influential or Dominant on another civ will speed the spread of plagues into their lands.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Cities connected to the local trade network are more likely to spread plagues in friendly lands.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]Healthy cities are less likely to contract Plague, and suffer from fewer turns of Plague once contracted.
				[NEWLINE][ICON_BULLET]If a civilization has ever been plagued, their spies (not Diplomats) have a small chance to unleash a plague when in foreign cities.
			</Text>
		</Row>
